WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.540 --> 00:00:02.930
Professor Amy
Hungerford: Okay.

00:00:02.930 --> 00:00:04.727
I'll go ahead and start,
just 'cause I am not sure how

00:00:04.727 --> 00:00:06.050
many people will end up being
here.

00:00:06.050 --> 00:00:09.414
So, as promised,
today I will tell you a little

00:00:09.414 --> 00:00:12.413
bit about the exam,
and I'll show you some

00:00:12.413 --> 00:00:16.655
questions from a past year so
that you can see what they're

00:00:16.655 --> 00:00:19.750
like.
We rewrite the exam every year.

00:00:19.750 --> 00:00:24.726
Even makeup exams are all
different, so I have a lot of

00:00:24.726 --> 00:00:30.017
these in my files.
The exam is two-and-a-half

00:00:30.017 --> 00:00:34.774
hours in a three-hour slot.
We have two rooms,

00:00:34.774 --> 00:00:39.204
'cause we have a big class.
They have given us this room

00:00:39.204 --> 00:00:44.414
and 102, so you can come to
either room for the event

00:00:44.414 --> 00:00:49.850
Friday, May 9,2:00pm to 5:00pm.
It has three parts.

00:00:49.850 --> 00:00:52.731
The first part is
identifications,

00:00:52.731 --> 00:00:57.010
and that's small things from
any of the novels.

00:00:57.010 --> 00:00:59.700
That could be a character.
It could be a place name.

00:00:59.700 --> 00:01:02.870
It could be even a couple of
words, a quotation,

00:01:02.870 --> 00:01:07.120
and you have to give the author
and title that it comes from,

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:12.106
of the book that it comes from,
and tell us what it is and a

00:01:12.106 --> 00:01:15.910
couple of sentences about its
significance,

00:01:15.910 --> 00:01:21.412
so why that thing is important.
Passages will be little

00:01:21.412 --> 00:01:26.623
chunks of text from a novel.
Again, you'll have to know

00:01:26.623 --> 00:01:30.230
author and title,
and then you will have to do an

00:01:30.230 --> 00:01:35.112
interpretation of the passage.
And then you have to say in a

00:01:35.112 --> 00:01:40.000
couple of sentences how that
passage as you have interpreted

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:43.480
it is important to the book as a
whole.

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:47.160
Oh, and you have to say the
context of the passage.

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:49.428
Now this might differ.
I'll give you a couple of

00:01:49.428 --> 00:01:51.040
examples.
This'll be different.

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:55.608
It might be a matter of saying
where in the plot it occurs or

00:01:55.608 --> 00:01:58.268
who, which character,
is speaking,

00:01:58.268 --> 00:02:02.130
what's going on in the scene
from which it's pulled,

00:02:02.130 --> 00:02:06.143
some sort of relevant context
so that we know that you

00:02:06.143 --> 00:02:09.400
understand where the thing comes
from.

00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:12.840
So you have fifteen minutes to
do each of those.

00:02:12.840 --> 00:02:18.400
The essay is 40% of the
final grade.

00:02:18.400 --> 00:02:20.994
You have a half an hour,
and--I'll show you--I have a

00:02:20.994 --> 00:02:22.789
special way of doing these
essays.

00:02:22.789 --> 00:02:25.229
Usually, they're big,
general questions.

00:02:25.229 --> 00:02:30.654
A good way to review for that
is to look at the old essay

00:02:30.654 --> 00:02:35.338
questions, the essay topics.
You'll find a lot of clues

00:02:35.338 --> 00:02:39.375
there about themes that unite
all the works on the syllabus,

00:02:39.375 --> 00:02:42.180
so that can be a good way of
studying.

00:02:42.180 --> 00:02:46.979
In each of these sections
you will get to choose.

00:02:46.979 --> 00:02:50.550
So, in the IDs usually I give
nine, and you get to choose six.

00:02:50.550 --> 00:02:53.127
In the passages,
I aim for seven and you choose

00:02:53.127 --> 00:02:55.629
four.
In the essays I always give

00:02:55.629 --> 00:03:00.102
three and you choose one.
Within the essays you can

00:03:00.102 --> 00:03:05.379
choose between two lists of
books to use to answer your

00:03:05.379 --> 00:03:08.577
questions.
You get to choose three of four

00:03:08.577 --> 00:03:12.059
on each of those two lists,
and I'll explain a little bit

00:03:12.059 --> 00:03:14.360
why I do that when I show you
one.

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:19.092
The one restriction on the
essay is that you may only write

00:03:19.092 --> 00:03:23.090
about one novel you've written a
long paper on,

00:03:23.090 --> 00:03:27.052
so only one of the three novels
that you choose to write about

00:03:27.052 --> 00:03:30.820
for the essay question can be
one that you wrote about in a

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:33.615
paper.
So your TF who will be grading

00:03:33.615 --> 00:03:37.690
the exam will know what you
wrote on, so just observe that

00:03:37.690 --> 00:03:41.382
guideline.
It's written in the directions

00:03:41.382 --> 00:03:43.477
of the exam.
Now, so,

00:03:43.477 --> 00:03:46.620
let me show you now what these
look like.

