00:13:16.190 --> 00:13:18.853
Uh huh. Eli.
Privilege Student:

00:13:18.853 --> 00:13:21.836
You could connect it to a
vision of morality,

00:13:21.836 --> 00:13:25.129
like the way Mildred and Henry
treat their slaves,

00:13:25.129 --> 00:13:36.118
related to the way God treats
his children…

00:13:36.118 --> 00:13:46.210
Professor Amy
Hungerford: Right.

00:13:46.210 --> 00:13:53.374
So both in your example of
Mildred and Henry--not Mildred,

00:13:53.374 --> 00:13:58.779
Henry and….Now I've lost
her name.

00:13:58.779 --> 00:14:00.750
What is her name,
his wife's name?

00:14:00.750 --> 00:14:04.865
Caldonia.
Henry and Caldonia have this

00:14:04.865 --> 00:14:09.804
vision of a pure morality that
they could sponsor in their

00:14:09.804 --> 00:14:13.841
slave-holding life,
and, similarly,

00:14:13.841 --> 00:14:19.832
this is Barnum Kinsey speaking.
You'd want to identify the

00:14:19.832 --> 00:14:23.950
speaker here.
Barnum Kinsey dreams of a pure

00:14:23.950 --> 00:14:29.740
space in which he could do the
morally right thing,

00:14:29.740 --> 00:14:33.913
but as Eli was saying this is a
novel in which no such space or

00:14:33.913 --> 00:14:37.200
light is possible,
so you'd want to note that.

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:43.725
That's more a thematic element
of this, but you would want to

00:14:43.725 --> 00:14:47.299
note that.
That's really important.

00:14:47.299 --> 00:14:49.759
Anything else that we might
want to say?

00:14:49.759 --> 00:14:52.888
Yes.Student:
Well, in the language he

00:14:52.888 --> 00:14:56.549
repeats "a body could say" and "
a body could stand,"

00:14:56.549 --> 00:14:59.632
and it's kind of a way of
preventing literary means of

00:14:59.632 --> 00:15:02.539
being excluding the
illiterate.Professor Amy

00:15:02.539 --> 00:15:04.720
Hungerford: Uh huh.
Yeah.

00:15:04.720 --> 00:15:06.710
I think you can definitely talk
about that.

00:15:06.710 --> 00:15:07.830
I think there are a couple of
ways.

00:15:07.830 --> 00:15:10.704
One is to associate it with
literacy so that just

00:15:10.704 --> 00:15:12.980
being is a way of
testifying,

00:15:12.980 --> 00:15:17.801
somehow, that Barnum,
in behaving the way he would

00:15:17.801 --> 00:15:22.426
have wanted to behave,
could have done the moral

00:15:22.426 --> 00:15:25.807
thing.
But there is a contrast here

00:15:25.807 --> 00:15:29.231
between saying it,
being the moral thing,

00:15:29.231 --> 00:15:34.196
and his having stood by as a
body in that scene and allowed

00:15:34.196 --> 00:15:37.450
Augustus to be sold into
slavery.

00:15:37.450 --> 00:15:42.750
So, you could certainly make
hay of that elocution.

00:15:42.750 --> 00:15:46.896
And, for any example that uses
dialect in this way,

00:15:46.896 --> 00:15:50.938
you do want to interrogate it.
So, don't just say,

00:15:50.938 --> 00:15:55.175
"Well, that's just trying to
sound like someone would sound

00:15:55.175 --> 00:15:59.279
like in this social situation."
Don't stop there.

00:15:59.279 --> 00:16:03.360
Know that the passages will be
chosen so that any irregularity

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:07.107
of language, even if it's for
the purposes of realism and

00:16:07.107 --> 00:16:09.489
dialect,
is probably going to be

00:16:09.489 --> 00:16:13.927
something you can talk about.
So, just be aware of that and

00:16:13.927 --> 00:16:19.094
creative in thinking about what
that variation in language could

00:16:19.094 --> 00:16:20.490
mean.
Okay.

