00:35:32.320 --> 00:35:36.862
Eli.Student:
I wanted to ask why "1945"

00:35:36.862 --> 00:35:41.033
is particularly
important.Professor Amy

00:35:41.033 --> 00:35:46.918
Hungerford: Why postwar?
Well, in America that marks two

00:35:46.918 --> 00:35:49.808
things for me.
One is the rise of the mass

00:35:49.808 --> 00:35:51.724
market and that
changes…Well,

00:35:51.724 --> 00:35:53.750
actually I would say three
things.

00:35:53.750 --> 00:35:57.524
The rise of the mass market
changes the relationship between

00:35:57.524 --> 00:36:00.659
readership and the literature
that's out there.

00:36:00.659 --> 00:36:05.168
So, it used to be that "high
literature" was not published in

00:36:05.168 --> 00:36:09.827
paperback, but the rise of the
mass-market paperback meant that

00:36:09.827 --> 00:36:14.110
suddenly books that would never
be accessible to a sort of

00:36:14.110 --> 00:36:18.017
average middle-class or
working-class person suddenly

00:36:18.017 --> 00:36:22.253
became so.
So, it's a huge watershed in

00:36:22.253 --> 00:36:27.360
the demographics of readership.
So, that's one reason.

00:36:27.360 --> 00:36:32.029
A second reason is related
to this, and that's that

00:36:32.029 --> 00:36:37.217
hundreds of thousands of men
came back and went to college on

00:36:37.217 --> 00:36:41.800
the GI Bill who had never been
to college before.

00:36:41.800 --> 00:36:44.050
Nobody in their families had
ever been to college before.

00:36:44.050 --> 00:36:46.920
This also changed the
readership dramatically.

00:36:46.920 --> 00:36:52.195
It was a time of an enormous
boom in college enrollments,

00:36:52.195 --> 00:36:57.659
and part of that was a huge
boom in English enrollments.

00:36:57.659 --> 00:37:02.729
Literature was a way for people
who had never been to college

00:37:02.729 --> 00:37:07.798
before to feel that they were
entering in to the upper middle

00:37:07.798 --> 00:37:12.867
class because it was a kind of
pursuit that was marked by its

00:37:12.867 --> 00:37:19.779
bourgeois prestige,
or its prestige marked you as

00:37:19.779 --> 00:37:23.503
bourgeois.
So, for people interested in

00:37:23.503 --> 00:37:27.380
raising their class status,
and that was lots of people,

00:37:27.380 --> 00:37:30.849
coming into the educational
system, higher education,

00:37:30.849 --> 00:37:34.320
for the first time,
literature was very important.

00:37:34.320 --> 00:37:40.308
There is a whole story about
why literature is no longer that

00:37:40.308 --> 00:37:46.496
class-marking enterprise that it
was at mid century that has to

00:37:46.496 --> 00:37:51.562
do with the rise of writing,
the competence in writing being

00:37:51.562 --> 00:37:54.884
more important than the
competence in literary tradition

00:37:54.884 --> 00:37:57.119
to mark you as an educated
person.

00:37:57.119 --> 00:38:02.783
So, that's an interesting story
in itself, but in general 1945

00:38:02.783 --> 00:38:07.625
is the beginning of that.
The third thing is that,

00:38:07.625 --> 00:38:12.378
by 1945, the innovations of
modernism are really very well

00:38:12.378 --> 00:38:15.684
established.
The big careers of early

00:38:15.684 --> 00:38:20.219
century literary enterprise are
totally established,

00:38:20.219 --> 00:38:23.720
and they have been assumed
almost fully into the

00:38:23.720 --> 00:38:28.039
institution of the university
through the New Criticism.

00:38:28.039 --> 00:38:31.960
The New Criticism was that
method of reading literature

00:38:31.960 --> 00:38:36.389
that was determining how people
were reading in classrooms,

00:38:36.389 --> 00:38:39.243
how all those new college
students were reading in

00:38:39.243 --> 00:38:42.947
classrooms.
That set the agenda for what

00:38:42.947 --> 00:38:47.896
would come next,
so in that context someone like

00:38:47.896 --> 00:38:52.624
John Barth,
trained intensively in the New

00:38:52.624 --> 00:38:59.458
Criticism, had to decide what he
was going to do as a literarily

00:38:59.458 --> 00:39:04.933
ambitious writer to innovate.
So, it was a question of,

00:39:04.933 --> 00:39:09.099
how could literature carry on
and do something new?

00:39:09.099 --> 00:39:11.150
And there are lots of different
answers to that.

00:39:11.150 --> 00:39:16.128
And another answer to it,
that is partly the result of

00:39:16.128 --> 00:39:19.360
the GI Bill explosion of
education,

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:22.995
that's the changing demographic
of who gets to read and who gets

00:39:22.995 --> 00:39:25.693
to write.
So, women, people of color,

00:39:25.693 --> 00:39:30.433
begin to change the agendas of
modernism simply by getting that

00:39:30.433 --> 00:39:33.719
education and entering into the
academy.

00:39:33.719 --> 00:39:35.670
So, Toni Morrison is a great
example of that.

00:39:35.670 --> 00:39:40.144
So is Maxine Hong Kingston.
There was this sense that

00:39:40.144 --> 00:39:45.736
modernism had not even begun to
touch on the experience of vast

00:39:45.736 --> 00:39:50.611
swaths of society,
and writers like Morrison and

00:39:50.611 --> 00:39:55.650
Kingston were very busy wanting
to rectify that.

00:39:55.650 --> 00:39:59.785
So, it marks a change that's
beyond just a change in

00:39:59.785 --> 00:40:02.177
readership.
The demographic change in

00:40:02.177 --> 00:40:05.066
readership and in education
really begins to change the

00:40:05.066 --> 00:40:10.880
agenda of literature.
So, that's why '45 is my marker.

00:40:10.880 --> 00:40:13.579
It's a crude one,
like all these things.

00:40:13.579 --> 00:40:16.250
You can't say,
"Well, why not 1942?"

00:40:16.250 --> 00:40:20.550
It doesn't quite work that
specifically.

00:40:20.550 --> 00:40:25.973
Okay.
