Student:

00:40:33.512 --> 00:40:35.230
Of the novels you read,
what are your favorite ones?

00:40:35.230 --> 00:40:37.820
I know you have them,
too.Professor Amy

00:40:37.820 --> 00:40:39.720
Hungerford: You do,
do you?

00:40:42.960 --> 00:40:43.979
Gosh.
That's really,

00:40:43.979 --> 00:40:46.030
really hard.
I do love The Known World.

00:40:46.030 --> 00:40:49.848
I really admire it.
I think it's genuinely doing

00:40:49.848 --> 00:40:53.155
something new,
and that's hard to do right

00:40:53.155 --> 00:40:53.720
now;

00:40:57.019 --> 00:40:58.329
so I love it,
and I loved it as a reading

00:40:58.329 --> 00:40:59.639
experience, even when I first
read it.

00:40:59.639 --> 00:41:01.889
It really captured my
imagination.

00:41:01.889 --> 00:41:05.440
I have always loved and hated
Blood Meridian.

00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:07.559
I love and hate Cormac
McCarthy.

00:41:07.559 --> 00:41:10.713
I've spent a lot of time
thinking about him,

00:41:10.713 --> 00:41:13.500
writing about him,
reading his work,

00:41:13.500 --> 00:41:20.004
and while I am really in awe of
his ability especially to use

00:41:20.004 --> 00:41:25.099
the far reaches of our
vocabulary in English.

00:41:25.099 --> 00:41:30.010
Talk about someone who really
makes room in the language.

00:41:30.010 --> 00:41:34.568
He can really do that.
If you read the first few pages

00:41:34.568 --> 00:41:38.762
of one of his earlier novels,
Suttree, you get a

00:41:38.762 --> 00:41:42.355
fantastic image of this.
It's a very Joycean novel,

00:41:42.355 --> 00:41:45.040
that one.
The vocabulary-- You just have

00:41:45.040 --> 00:41:49.016
to look up every third word.
It's really incredible.And

00:41:49.016 --> 00:41:52.565
I'm really interested in the way
he is focused on craft,

00:41:52.565 --> 00:41:55.469
both as a writer,
but all kinds of crafts.

00:41:55.469 --> 00:41:59.039
He has this play called The
Last Stonemason.

00:41:59.039 --> 00:42:02.186
I think it's called The
Last Stonemason or just

00:42:02.186 --> 00:42:04.389
The Stonemason.
The Stonemason.

00:42:04.389 --> 00:42:08.785
He's interested in these
old arts, physical arts like

00:42:08.785 --> 00:42:12.073
forging.
There's a great chapter on

00:42:12.073 --> 00:42:17.368
smithing in a novel called
The Child of God where

00:42:17.368 --> 00:42:23.049
the language of the smithy is
folded into this meditation on

00:42:23.049 --> 00:42:26.741
aesthetics,
talks about what color the fire

00:42:26.741 --> 00:42:30.696
and the metal should be at every
moment of reforging an ax

00:42:30.696 --> 00:42:33.590
handle.
Of course, in true McCarthy

00:42:33.590 --> 00:42:38.480
style, the ax handle will then
be used to chop up dead bodies

00:42:38.480 --> 00:42:42.066
and skin people,
so that's very McCarthyesque

00:42:42.066 --> 00:42:44.761
too.
But at the same time I just

00:42:44.761 --> 00:42:49.620
find him frustratingly empty.
The Road I adored.

00:42:49.620 --> 00:42:53.147
It was a terrifying read.
I had insomnia one night,

00:42:53.147 --> 00:42:56.681
and I started to read it at
about 1:30 in the morning,

00:42:56.681 --> 00:43:00.150
and I finished it about 5:30
and I was terrified.

00:43:00.150 --> 00:43:04.320
Have I told you about The
Road, what it's about?

00:43:04.320 --> 00:43:07.756
It takes place ten years into a
nuclear winter,

00:43:07.756 --> 00:43:12.014
and it's about a father and son
making their way down from

00:43:12.014 --> 00:43:16.063
Appalachia to the Gulf Coast,
for no apparent reason except

00:43:16.063 --> 00:43:19.393
that the father seems to think
that somehow they'll be able to

00:43:19.393 --> 00:43:21.849
survive better once they get to
the coast.

00:43:21.849 --> 00:43:25.569
Meanwhile, in this world,
there are all these

00:43:25.569 --> 00:43:28.949
cannibalistic gangs that have
started.

00:43:28.949 --> 00:43:33.099
Women are used to produce
babies that they then eat.

00:43:33.099 --> 00:43:36.858
It's really completely bleak
and terrifying and the

00:43:36.858 --> 00:43:40.992
relationship between the father
and the son is extremely

00:43:40.992 --> 00:43:43.836
touching,
and I have a little boy who is

00:43:43.836 --> 00:43:47.072
about the same age and oh,
my God, I was just--it was

00:43:47.072 --> 00:43:50.805
really terrifying to read this
all alone in the middle of the

00:43:50.805 --> 00:43:53.471
night.
I sort of got in bed with my

00:43:53.471 --> 00:43:57.293
son later and just kind of
cuddled with him to remember

00:43:57.293 --> 00:44:03.929
that he was still alive.But,
at the end, there is this sense

00:44:03.929 --> 00:44:09.228
of the boy carrying the light.
The father says,

00:44:09.228 --> 00:44:13.670
"We're carrying the light.
We're the good guys."

00:44:13.670 --> 00:44:15.559
And the son sort of repeats
that.

00:44:15.559 --> 00:44:18.549
By the end--and I won't tell
you what happens 'cause you

00:44:18.549 --> 00:44:21.920
should read it--but there is
this affirmation of that light,

00:44:21.920 --> 00:44:24.059
but what the light is,
who knows?

00:44:24.059 --> 00:44:26.780
There is sort of a Promethean
narrative there.

00:44:26.780 --> 00:44:29.269
There is also a messianic
narrative there.

00:44:29.269 --> 00:44:32.187
I think, personally,
my own meaning of it,

00:44:32.187 --> 00:44:35.959
is that it's McCarthy
meditating on the end of his own

00:44:35.959 --> 00:44:38.510
life.
McCarthy is a very old man with

00:44:38.510 --> 00:44:41.222
a very young son,
and I think he was thinking

00:44:41.222 --> 00:44:45.051
about his own death.
And the fate of the father in

00:44:45.051 --> 00:44:49.126
that novel, I think,
is very much about McCarthy's

00:44:49.126 --> 00:44:52.962
sense of himself.
So yeah, McCarthy is a tough

00:44:52.962 --> 00:44:55.262
one.
Marilynne Robinson I like a

00:44:55.262 --> 00:44:58.829
lot also.
I like the beauty of her prose.

00:44:58.829 --> 00:45:02.893
That biblical cadence that she
and McCarthy both have I really

00:45:02.893 --> 00:45:05.010
like.
I love the outdoor imagery,

00:45:05.010 --> 00:45:07.150
the nature imagery,
of that novel.

00:45:07.150 --> 00:45:14.670
And I love Roth for my own
obscure and perverse reasons.

00:45:14.670 --> 00:45:18.108
Yeah.
So I sort of have my favorites,

00:45:18.108 --> 00:45:22.056
but I like them--I,
really, there are things that I

00:45:22.056 --> 00:45:26.163
like about all of them.
An interesting story about

00:45:26.163 --> 00:45:28.769
liking novels:
I hated Salinger.

00:45:28.769 --> 00:45:32.676
I really hated Salinger,
because I found him so

00:45:32.676 --> 00:45:36.399
pretentious and affected.
I just hated that tone of

00:45:36.399 --> 00:45:39.888
voice, until I was working on
this book on religion and I read

00:45:39.888 --> 00:45:43.148
Franny and Zooey.
And here you can tell most

00:45:43.148 --> 00:45:46.579
of my great thought happens in
the middle of the night.

00:45:46.579 --> 00:45:48.713
So, I had been thinking about
Franny and Zooey,

00:45:48.713 --> 00:45:50.694
and I suddenly woke up in
the middle of the night

00:45:50.694 --> 00:45:52.816
thinking,
"I know what style is for in

00:45:52.816 --> 00:45:56.245
Franny and Zooey!"
So, I got up and I wrote it

00:45:56.245 --> 00:45:58.691
down,
and that lecture that I gave on

00:45:58.691 --> 00:46:01.760
Franny and Zooey is part
of my new book.

00:46:01.760 --> 00:46:06.489
And when the book was reviewed
for presses, a part of it,

00:46:06.489 --> 00:46:11.303
one of my readers said it was
the best reading he had ever

00:46:11.303 --> 00:46:16.571
seen of contemporary fiction.
And it made me love Franny

00:46:16.571 --> 00:46:21.620
and Zooey 'cause suddenly I
had something to think about

00:46:21.620 --> 00:46:25.300
other than well,
this is so pretentious.

00:46:25.300 --> 00:46:30.119
I had a reason why that tone
and that style was there.

00:46:30.119 --> 00:46:34.476
So, thinking about books can
really change your sense of

00:46:34.476 --> 00:46:38.516
whether you like them or not in
a self--I know--in a

00:46:38.516 --> 00:46:41.950
self-serving way.
Now who's pretentious?

00:46:41.950 --> 00:46:44.640
Okay.
