00:50:00.915 --> 00:50:04.260
robes, and she pretends to be
that priest.

00:50:04.260 --> 00:50:07.397
And she becomes--she
cross-dresses and is the priest

00:50:07.397 --> 00:50:09.920
at the reservation for her
entire life.

00:50:09.920 --> 00:50:14.550
And I just think it's a
fascinating premise for a novel,

00:50:14.550 --> 00:50:19.769
and it's very well done and her
language is quite wonderful.

00:50:19.769 --> 00:50:23.846
Again, I am ambivalent about
it, because I find the ending

00:50:23.846 --> 00:50:26.819
facile.
It finally resolves all the

00:50:26.819 --> 00:50:31.822
problems that this situation
produces in a way that I don't

00:50:31.822 --> 00:50:35.789
find complex enough,
or challenging enough.

00:50:35.789 --> 00:50:39.644
It's just too easy to make it
all come together the way she

00:50:39.644 --> 00:50:41.790
does.
So, that's one.

00:50:41.790 --> 00:50:46.620
Let me think.
There are many,

00:50:46.620 --> 00:50:49.633
many other novels.
I'm perpetually torn whether to

00:50:49.633 --> 00:50:52.486
put The Road on,
or Blood Meridian,

00:50:52.486 --> 00:50:54.500
or some other McCarthy
novel.

00:50:54.500 --> 00:51:01.023
I've taught at least four
different Roth novels spanning

00:51:01.023 --> 00:51:05.530
the period from 1960 to the
present.

00:51:05.530 --> 00:51:09.750
Other writers…
Now, I don't know why I'm

00:51:09.750 --> 00:51:12.870
blanking, now that I think about
this.

00:51:17.019 --> 00:51:19.440
Who else would I like to put on
there?

00:51:19.440 --> 00:51:22.280
Oh, Eggers.
Now I "fess up."

00:51:22.280 --> 00:51:26.146
I really would have loved to do
What is the What as our

00:51:26.146 --> 00:51:29.034
last novel.
Now, Eggers started out

00:51:29.034 --> 00:51:34.421
immature, in the same way that,
I think, Jonathan Safran Foer

00:51:34.421 --> 00:51:35.922
is.
But he grew up,

00:51:35.922 --> 00:51:39.840
and it's a beautiful thing.
So, A Heartbreaking Work of

00:51:39.840 --> 00:51:43.657
Staggering Genius has a lot
of that sort of kind of

00:51:43.657 --> 00:51:47.289
clichéd,
postmodern trickery in it,

00:51:47.289 --> 00:51:52.010
but by the time he gets to
What is the What,

00:51:52.010 --> 00:51:55.510
 that novel is like
nothing else.

00:51:55.510 --> 00:51:59.076
There is no equivalent of that
novel, to my knowledge,

00:51:59.076 --> 00:52:02.989
anywhere in our tradition.
It's just an astonishing

00:52:02.989 --> 00:52:07.809
inhabitation of another person's
life, but in real time.

00:52:07.809 --> 00:52:12.320
I was able to have dinner with
him and some other people when

00:52:12.320 --> 00:52:16.230
he came as the Schlesinger
writer a few years ago,

00:52:16.230 --> 00:52:21.650
and I said, "Did you find it
confining to give yourself over

00:52:21.650 --> 00:52:26.520
in that creative way to this
other person's story?"

00:52:26.520 --> 00:52:28.219
And he said, "Yeah.
It was terrible.

00:52:28.219 --> 00:52:31.920
I'd be writing 'The truck went
down the road.'"

00:52:31.920 --> 00:52:36.197
He'd have to call Valentino and
say, "Valentino,

00:52:36.197 --> 00:52:40.840
that truck--was the road
gravel, or was it paved?

00:52:40.840 --> 00:52:44.063
And was it dusty?
Was there stuff kicking up,

00:52:44.063 --> 00:52:47.435
or was it just flat?"
It was just amazing,

00:52:47.435 --> 00:52:52.348
the degree to which he put his
writing pen at the service of

00:52:52.348 --> 00:52:57.003
another person and their story.
It's really remarkable,

00:52:57.003 --> 00:53:00.175
so, given that extremely
confining setup,

00:53:00.175 --> 00:53:04.139
he makes that novel truly
literary, in my mind.

00:53:04.139 --> 00:53:08.923
It has a real form,
it has a very lively voice,

00:53:08.923 --> 00:53:13.500
and it's extremely powerful and
affecting.

00:53:13.500 --> 00:53:15.619
So, that's something I would
love to have,

00:53:15.619 --> 00:53:18.410
but again it's a huge novel,
so this is the problem.

00:53:18.410 --> 00:53:21.267
It's so long.
I think I just need two

00:53:21.267 --> 00:53:23.180
semesters.
I think that would be better.

00:53:23.180 --> 00:53:24.280
Yes.
Student:

00:53:24.280 --> 00:53:25.398
What about Jonathan Safran
Foer's latest

00:53:25.398 --> 00:53:26.827
book?Professor Amy
Hungerford: I haven't read

00:53:26.827 --> 00:53:30.164
it yet,
but I have to say the reviews

00:53:30.164 --> 00:53:35.692
that I hear about it--so,
was it Extremely Loud and

00:53:35.692 --> 00:53:41.532
Incredibly Close?--the
structure of the plot makes me

00:53:41.532 --> 00:53:43.737
doubt,
a little bit,

00:53:43.737 --> 00:53:49.141
because it's just another hunt.
So, it's this nine-year-old boy

00:53:49.141 --> 00:53:54.292
who loses his father on 9/11,
and he finds in his father's

00:53:54.292 --> 00:53:58.630
effects a key that's marked
"Black," I think.

00:53:58.630 --> 00:54:02.436
It has a little label on it,
and so he goes around in New

00:54:02.436 --> 00:54:06.378
York City finding everyone by
the name of Black that he can

00:54:06.378 --> 00:54:08.282
find.
So, it has this structure

00:54:08.282 --> 00:54:10.920
that's so similar to
Everything is Illuminated.

00:54:10.920 --> 00:54:14.934
That hunt structure just
made me think,

00:54:14.934 --> 00:54:19.809
I wonder whether this is just a
one-trick writer,

00:54:19.809 --> 00:54:24.699
that he has this idea and this
is what it's always going to be?

00:54:24.699 --> 00:54:28.128
That doesn't necessarily mean
that someone is not a great

00:54:28.128 --> 00:54:30.654
writer.
Roth is kind of a one-trick

00:54:30.654 --> 00:54:32.409
pony, in this way,
too.

00:54:32.409 --> 00:54:37.570
He has his own repetitions from
novel to novel.

00:54:37.570 --> 00:54:40.751
Most writers I know do,
but that seemed a little

00:54:40.751 --> 00:54:44.610
too--It was a little too close
for me, so I don't know.

00:54:44.610 --> 00:54:45.650
I have to find time to read it.

00:54:48.750 --> 00:54:50.659
Denis Johnson:
I did actually-- I was very

00:54:50.659 --> 00:54:53.267
interested in having Jesus'
Son as the last novel,

00:54:53.267 --> 00:54:56.006
too.
I'm going to write a review for

00:54:56.006 --> 00:55:00.511
the Yale Review on Denis
Johnson's work by the end of

00:55:00.511 --> 00:55:04.252
July, so by then I'll know what
I think about him,

00:55:04.252 --> 00:55:06.380
too.
Other questions?

00:55:06.380 --> 00:55:10.100
Or shall I let you go?
Any other questions?

00:55:10.100 --> 00:55:12.545
Okay.
So I will see you at the exam,

00:55:12.545 --> 00:55:15.553
and I think some sections are
having review sessions,

00:55:15.553 --> 00:55:17.086
so check with your TF.
 

